I’ll give you the proper production sequence.

✅ Step 1 — Generate Private Key
openssl genrsa -out ibmmq-client.key 2048
✅ Step 2 — Create CSR (Certificate Signing Request)

Use correct DN structure (based on your page).

Example NON-PROD (HK, DEV):
openssl req -new \
  -key ibmmq-client.key \
  -out ibmmq-client.csr \
  -subj "/CN=APPA_DEV/O=AP/OU=AUTHENC/L=MQCDEV/C=HK"

Adjust:

CN = <AppCode>_DEV or _PROD

L = MQCDEV or MQCPROD

O = AP / EU / NA

C = HK / GB / US / FR

That CSR goes to SNOW.

✅ Step 3 — When You Receive Signed Client Certificate

Let’s say they give you:

signed_client_cert.pem
✅ Step 4 — Build Full Certificate Chain File

MQ and Kafka often want full chain.

Create:

cat signed_client_cert.pem \
    hsbc-issuing-ca02-g2.pem \
    hsbc-orca-g2.pem \
    > ibmmq-client-fullchain.pem

Order is critical:

[ Client Cert ]
[ Intermediate ]
[ Root ]
✅ Step 5 — Verify Chain
openssl verify \
  -CAfile <(cat hsbc-orca-g2.pem hsbc-issuing-ca02-g2.pem) \
  signed_client_cert.pem

Should return:

signed_client_cert.pem: OK
🔥 If You Need PKCS12 (For Kafka / Java Later)

Even if you’re OpenSSL-only now, this is how to convert:

openssl pkcs12 -export \
  -in ibmmq-client-fullchain.pem \
  -inkey ibmmq-client.key \
  -out ibmmq-client.p12 \
  -name ibmmq-client
