Good. Now we narrow it properly.

For Kafka Connect → IBM MQ Sink Connector over TLS, using OpenSSL artifacts, you need this:

Kafka (Java) does NOT use raw PEM key + cert directly.
It needs PKCS12 or JKS.

Since you want OpenSSL-only, we’ll generate everything with OpenSSL and then produce a PKCS12 for Kafka.

🔥 Correct Flow for Kafka MQ Sink Connector (mTLS)

You need:

Client private key

Signed client certificate

Full chain

PKCS12 keystore

Truststore (CA only)

✅ 1. Generate Private Key
openssl genrsa -out ibmmq-client.key 2048
✅ 2. Create CSR

Example (NON-PROD HK DEV):

openssl req -new \
  -key ibmmq-client.key \
  -out ibmmq-client.csr \
  -subj "/CN=APPA_DEV/O=AP/OU=AUTHENC/L=MQCDEV/C=HK"

Send ibmmq-client.csr to SNOW.

✅ 3. When You Receive Signed Cert

Assume:

signed_client_cert.pem
✅ 4. Build Full Chain
cat signed_client_cert.pem \
    hsbc-issuing-ca02-g2.pem \
    hsbc-orca-g2.pem \
    > ibmmq-client-fullchain.pem

Order matters:

Client

Intermediate

Root

✅ 5. Create PKCS12 Keystore (THIS is what Kafka needs)
openssl pkcs12 -export \
  -in ibmmq-client-fullchain.pem \
  -inkey ibmmq-client.key \
  -name ibmmq-client \
  -out ibmmq-client.p12

Set a password.

✅ 6. Create Truststore PKCS12 (CA only)

Kafka also needs truststore.

cat hsbc-issuing-ca02-g2.pem \
    hsbc-orca-g2.pem \
    > ca-chain.pem

Then:

openssl pkcs12 -export \
  -in ca-chain.pem \
  -nokeys \
  -name mq-ca \
  -out mq-truststore.p12
